    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zflGZ.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 440158,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 829571,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/829571/assylias",
                "reputation": 330070,
                "display_name": "assylias",
                "accept_rate": 94
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1422041768,
            "creation_date": 1422041768,
            "body": "<p>With Java 8 you could use something similar to the following:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>import static java.util.Comparator.comparing;\n\nmap.entrySet().stream()\n   .sorted(comparing(Entry::getKey))\n   .forEach(e -&gt; doSomethingWithTheEntry(e));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>That will obviously involve sorting the unsorted keys, which will come at a cost. So you need to decide whether you want to pay the cost upfront with a TreeMap or when required and keep using a HashMap.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 28117419,
            "question_id": 28117279
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/jXcg4.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1263831,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1221571,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1221571/eran",
                "reputation": 395099,
                "display_name": "Eran",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1713163771,
            "creation_date": 1422041425,
            "body": "<p>You can't iterate over a <code>HashMap<\/code> in order (such as the numerical order of the keys). The iteration order in which you'll encounter the keys/values/entries of the <code>HashMap<\/code> is implementation dependent and should not be relied upon.<\/p>\n<p>You can use a <code>TreeMap<\/code> for your desired iteration order. If you use a <code>LinkedHashMap<\/code>, you can iterate in the order the keys were inserted to the <code>Map<\/code>, but it's still not what you want (unless you insert the keys in numerical order).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 28117331,
            "question_id": 28117279,
            "last_edit_date": 1713163771
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2aafa2e5771893676c471305bae105aa?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 4082028,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3352285,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3352285/nespowerglove",
                "reputation": 5496,
                "display_name": "NESPowerGlove"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1422041551,
            "creation_date": 1422041551,
            "body": "<p>If your insertion order is the same order as your keys, then you could use a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/LinkedHashMap.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">LinkedHashMap<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Hash table and linked list implementation of the Map interface, with predictable iteration order. This implementation differs from HashMap in that it maintains a doubly-linked list running through all of its entries. This linked list defines the iteration ordering, which is normally the order in which keys were inserted into the map (insertion-order). Note that insertion order is not affected if a key is re-inserted into the map. (A key k is reinserted into a map m if m.put(k, v) is invoked when m.containsKey(k) would return true immediately prior to the invocation.)<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 28117358,
            "question_id": 28117279
        }
    ],
